mically coherent.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Retain Fe2+ explicitly as the hydrothermal catalyst in rxn_002 metadata.\",\n        \"Add literature-backed sourcing or external availability assumption for hydroxylamine.\",\n        \"Discuss pyruvate thermal instability as a possible competing sink.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.91\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.79,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.96,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n      \"feedback\": \"A strong hydrothermal route anchored in experimentally supported iron chemistry. Like P3, it is mainly limited by the unsupported origin of hydroxylamine. Otherwise, decarboxylation of oxaloacetate to pyruvate and conversion of pyruvate to alanine are both well supported by the cited literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Improve hydroxylamine sourcing.\",\n        \"Specify whether water release in variant B reflects net bookkeeping.\",\n        \"Consider including a concentration mechanism for pyruvate prior to amination.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.92\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"Good cross-environment logic: surface cyanosulfidic chemistry feeds pyruvate into hydrothermal alanine synthesis. However, the surface oxaloacetate decarboxylation step is somewhat underspecified, and the hydroxylamine-generation step remains the major weakness. Environmental interconnection is a strength here, but chemical support is weaker than in the purely hydrothermal oxaloacetate routes.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify the mineral/photochemical context for the cyanosulfidic oxaloacetate decarboxylation step.\",\n        \"Add a literature-grounded transport rationale from surface pools to hydrothermal zones.\",\n        \"Replace ammonia-to-hydroxylamine with a better supported precursor pathway.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.91\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway benefits from strong environmental interconnection but remains limited by the same hydroxylamine issue. The surface-to-hydrothermal transfer is plausible in a network sense, though not strongly quantified. The pyruvate-to-alanine step is well supported, but precursor assembly is not fully convincing.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Support surface oxaloacetate decarboxylation with clearer experimental conditions.\",\n        \"Strengthen justification for hydroxylamine production and preservation.\",\n        \"Clarify whether pyruvate formed at the surface is stable enough for transfer.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.92\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.91,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"Lactate oxidation to pyruvate under cyanosulfidic conditions is literature-backed in broad terms, and the transfer to hydrothermal alanine synthesis is conceptually good. Still, the pathway is constrained by the poorly justified hydroxylamine-generation step. As a network connector, this is useful; as a fully evidenced path, it is weaker than the hydrothermal pyruvate routes.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Provide more explicit conditions and agents for lactate oxidation.\",\n        \"Address hydroxylamine sourcing from a literature-supported route.\",\n        \"Discuss possible competition from pyruvate decomposition before amination.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.91\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.91,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"A reasonable hybrid route in topology and environmental flow, but not among the strongest chemically. The final reductive amination remains solid; the weak point is again hydroxylamine formation. This pathway is acceptable as part of a network but not as a best-supported standalone route.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_010\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace the hydroxylamine source step.\",\n        \"State whether sulfur species or UV are required in the lactate oxidation environment.\",\n        \"Add concentration/transport assumptions linking surface pyruvate to hydrothermal iron chemistry.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.52,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.97\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.69,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.76,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"The terminal nitrile hydrolysis step is strongly supported by Patel et al. (2015). However, the upstream formation of 2-aminopropanenitrile from only HCN and NH3 is too compressed and chemically underspecified; Strecker/cyanosulfidic formation typically requires carbonyl precursors and additional context. Thus the route reaches alanine, but the precursor synthesis is not adequately represented.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_009\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand aminonitrile formation to include a carbonyl precursor such as acetaldehyde or pyruvate-derived chemistry.\",\n        \"Specify cyanosulfidic agents and conditions more explicitly.\",\n        \"Retain nitrile hydrolysis as a strong final step but improve upstream realism.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.62,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"The single-step serine reduction to alanine is literature-supported and chemically plausible in submarine hydrothermal systems. However, as a pathway it is underconnected because the network does not explain how serine is produced or delivered, so coherence is weaker than the pyruvate-centered routes. It is a valid terminal branch but not a complete best path from simple feedstocks.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add