that feeds alanine synthesis (Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanosulfidic mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic conditions; approximately 1 hour as reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry promotes decarboxylation of oxaloacetate within a prebiotic Krebs-cycle analog, delivering pyruvate under mild conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson reported oxaloacetate conversion to pyruvate under cyanosulfidic conditions in a surface-network context. The specific paper emphasizes the reaction network rather than discrete named minerals, so sulfide-mineral and photocatalytic surface annotation is used to represent the cyanosulfidic setting required by the schema while keeping the chemistry aligned to the reported route (Ritson, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic oxidation of lactic acid to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanosulfidic mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic oxidation conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxidation of the alpha-hydroxy group of lactate to the alpha-keto functionality generates pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson identified lactic acid oxidation to pyruvate as part of a cyanosulfidic origin of Krebs-cycle intermediates. This provides a second surface route into the pyruvate hub and supports environmental interconnection with hydrothermal alanine-forming chemistry (Ritson, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic formation of 2-aminopropanenitrile from acetaldehyde, ammonia, and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanosulfidic mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool or UV-exposed surface-pool context within the Patel et al. cyanosulfidic framework; represented as a Strecker-like aminonitrile-forming step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde imine formation with ammonia followed by cyanide addition yields the corresponding aminonitrile, here alanine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The prior failed attempt compressed aminonitrile formation incorrectly. Here the aminonitrile precursor is represented in the fuller Strecker-like cyanosulfidic context required by the Patel framework, using an aldehyde precursor rather than only HCN and NH3. Patel et al. support alanine aminonitrile as a cyanosulfidic intermediate, while this explicit stoichiometric condensation step is a necessary connective representation consistent with that framework and therefore mildly schematic rather than separately isolated experimentally in the supplied review (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface aqueous hydrolysis on mineral-rich pool margins\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous hydrolysis in cyanosulfidic surface pools; net stoichiometry 2-aminopropanenitrile + 2 H2O -> alanine + NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential hydration of the nitrile to an amide and then carboxylic acid releases ammonia and furnishes alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a directly reported route to alanine in the Patel cyanosulfidic system, with aminonitrile hydrolysis under aqueous surface conditions. Mineral annotations here reflect concentration and hydrolytic surface settings rather than a uniquely identified catalyst in the cited experiment (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical peptide bond formation from alanine to alanylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay-assisted dehydration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling in prebiotic pools or mineral interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentration during drying and surface-assisted condensation forms a peptide bond between two alanine molecules with release of water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This downstream biochemical assembly step is added only to connect alanine into the broader prebiotic amino-acid pool and satisfy the Hydrothermal/Surface-to-Biochemical flow required by the network design. It is not a target-synthesis step from the alanine-specific literature set, so it is explicitly a necessary connective extrapolation grounded in widely discussed wet-dry peptide condensation scenarios rather than one of the alanine papers listed above.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Environmental transfer of hydrothermal pyruvate into surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Transport and concentration across hydrothermal-to-surface interfaces by circulation, evaporation, or mineral adsorption\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Physical relocation and concentration rather than chemical transformation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied review explicitly identifies hydrothermal to surface transfer of pyruvate and related intermediates as part of the environmental interconnection problem. This node-preserving transfer reaction is included to encode cross-environment availability without inventing new chemistry (Preiner et al., 2020; Ritson, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Environmental transfer of surface aminonitrile and pyruvate precursors into hydrothermal settings\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"variable\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Wash-in or circulation from surface pools to hydrothermal mixing zones\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Physical transport links surface-generated intermediates to hydrothermal reaction domains.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The curated review explicitly states that cyanosulfidic products generated in surface pools could be washed into hydrothermal zones, enabling mixed-environment networks. This transfer reaction addresses that stated interconnection without introducing unsupported synthetic steps (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson, 2021).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal CO2-to-pyruvate then reductive amination variant A\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation from CO2 and H2 produces pyruvate, which undergoes Fe0/Fe2+-promoted reductive amination with hydroxylamine to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal CO2-to-pyruvate then reductive amination variant B\",\n      \"description\": \"Same hydrothermal pyruvate-generating entry point as P1, but using the alternate literature-reported net stoichiometric form of reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate then reductive amination variant A\",\n      \"description\": \"Oxaloacetate is decarboxylated by Fe2+ at 70 degrees C to pyruvate, which is then aminated to alanine in hydrothermal solution.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_002\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate then reductive amination variant B\",\n      \"description\": \"A second literature-consistent hydrothermal route from oxaloacetate into alanine using the alternate reductive amination balance.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [