t and topologically valuable because it converges on pyruvate before the final amination.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Explicitly identify Fe2+ as catalyst for oxaloacetate decarboxylation.\",\n        \"Note pyruvate thermal lability as a possible kinetic constraint.\",\n        \"Document whether oxaloacetate is imported from another environment or generated in-network.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.93,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.91,\n      \"feedback\": \"Strong hydrothermal pathway using literature-supported decarboxylation and the alternate reductive amination balance. It is a credible convergent route to alanine centered on pyruvate.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Include temperature around 343 K for both steps to align tightly with Muchowska et al. (2019).\",\n        \"Clarify racemic outcome.\",\n        \"Provide provenance for oxaloacetate availability.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.2,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.66,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.63,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.7,\n      \"feedback\": \"The chemical core is plausible because surface oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate and hydrothermal pyruvate amination are both literature-supported. However, the pathway depends on rxn_011, which is not a chemical reaction but an environmental transfer placeholder. That weakens bipartite graph v