ent with Ritson (2021), and pyruvate reductive amination is strong. But again, the pathway is impaired by the non-chemical transfer self-loop. Environmental interconnection is conceptually present but formally implemented poorly.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Model transport separately from chemistry.\",\n        \"Specify oxidant/sulfur species and mineral context for lactate oxidation.\",\n        \"Keep pyruvate as the cross-environment hub but do not encode transfer as identity reaction.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.2,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.67,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.63,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.7,\n      \"feedback\": \"Chemically reasonable endpoints, but the pathway is dragged below approval by the same invalid transfer node issue. The route would be much stronger if environmental movement were not encoded as a reaction.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Eliminate rxn_011 from pathway accounting.\",\n        \"Retain lactate-to-pyruvate as a convergent upstream route but describe relocation of pyruvate narratively.\",\n        \"Provide specific surface agents for the cyanosulfidic oxidation step.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.94\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.9,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"Strong surface route. Aminonitrile formation from