\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0) and ferrous iron (Fe2+)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"iron-promoted reductive amination in water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of hydroxylamine-derived nitrogen with the alpha-keto group of pyruvate followed by iron-mediated reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska, Varma, and Moran experimentally demonstrated conversion of pyruvate and hydroxylamine to alanine at 70 degrees C in water using Fe0 and Fe2+; this is one of the strongest literature-supported alanine-forming steps (Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine (variant B)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"ferrous iron (Fe2+)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0) and ferrous iron (Fe2+)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"overall balance represented as pyruvate + hydroxylamine -> alanine + water equivalents under iron-driven aqueous conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iron-promoted reductive amination of pyruvate by hydroxylamine with net dehydration in the overall stoichiometric representation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A second experimentally reported stoichiometric representation of pyruvate-to-alanine reductive amination was given in the same iron-driven network study, under the same 70 degrees C Fe0/Fe2+ hydrothermal conditions (Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-rich cyanosulfidic evaporitic pool setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ambient aqueous hydrolysis; stoichiometry represents 2-aminopropanenitrile + 2 H2O -> alanine + NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nucleophilic hydration of the nitrile to an amide/carboxylate stage followed by release of ammonia to furnish alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel and co-workers placed alanine formation within a cyanosulfidic protometabolism where 2-aminopropanenitrile hydrolyzes in aqueous surface settings to alanine and ammonia; this direct route is experimentally grounded, though the literature indicates racemic rather than enantioselective output (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of serine to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"hydrothermal mineral surfaces with H2 as reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"submarine hydrothermal conditions with elevated temperature and pressure; H2 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive dehydroxylation of serine side chain converting hydroxymethyl to methyl, yielding alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada reported reduction of serine to alanine by H2 under submarine hydrothermal conditions, linking hydrothermal amino acid interconversion to alanine production (Aubrey et al., 2008). The exact mineral phase was not specified in the report, so the listed hydrothermal iron minerals are contextual vent surfaces consistent with the required hydrothermal mineral field.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical wet-dry condensation of alanine to alanylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces; net stoichiometry represents 2 alanine -> alanylalanine + H2O\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrative peptide bond formation from concentrated alanine pools during repeated drying and rehydration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This downstream assembly step is added strictly to connect alanine into the broader prebiotic biochemical stage required by the network specification; it is a general prebiotic peptide-condensation step rather than an alanine-synthesis step and is included to show how literature-supported alanine products feed onward into proto-biochemical chemistry. The alanine source remains supported by Patel et al. (2015), Muchowska et al. (2019), Aubrey et al. (2008), Preiner et al. (2020), and Ritson (2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination-style linkage between pyruvate and alanine pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350 K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n      